SIMPLE: organization
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Organization
<hw>Or`gan*i*za"tion</hw>
<pr>(⟦ocir⟧r`g⟦ait⟧n*⟦imac⟧*z⟦amac⟧"sh⟦ucr⟧n)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>
<ety>[Cf. F. <ets>organisation</ets>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of organizing; the act of arranging in a
systematic way for use or action; <as>as, the <ex>organization</ex> of
an army, or of a deliberative body</as>.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧The first
<xex>organization</xex> of the general government.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Pickering.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The state of being organized.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>That which is organized; an organized existence; an
organism</def>; <specif>specif.</specif> <fld>(Biol.)</fld>, <def>an
arrangement of parts for the performance of the functions necessary to
life.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The cell may be regarded as the most simple, the most common, and
the earliest form of <qex>organization</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>McKendrick.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <specif>Specifically:</specif> <def>A group of persons
associated together for a common purpose and having a set of rules which
specify the relations of the individual members to the whole
gorup.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>The manner in which something is organized; the
relations included in an organized state or condition; <as>as, the
<ex>organization</ex> of the department permits ad hoc groups to
form</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><q>What is <qex>organization</qex> but the connection of parts in and
for a whole, so that each part is, at once, end and means?</q>
<rj><qau>Coleridge.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>organizational</ent>⟦br⟧
